"SECTION5_PARAGRAPH3" = "Getting back into exercising can feel challenging, especially at first. It’s important to listen to your body and be patient with where you are in your postpartum journey. It’s okay to slow down, modify positions or change routines. Make sure to stay hydrated, and always listen to your body. If you have any concerns, talk to your care team.";
"SECTION5_PARAGRAPH2" = "The goal is to eventually work your way up to 150 minutes of exercise a week. When it makes sense, returning to the types of exercise you were doing before pregnancy may help. It can be challenging to know what exercise is right for you and what feels best may change from day to day.";
"SECTION3_PARAGRAPH4" = "Exercises you’re familiar with also tend to be lower risk. If you had a regular exercise routine, you may be able to continue with it during pregnancy. For example, runners can often continue to engage in that activity for the majority of their pregnancy. Ask your care team if you’re not sure about your existing exercise routines but would like to continue them.";
"SECTION4_PARAGRAPH1" = "Just like before pregnancy, the recommendation is to get at least 150 minutes a week of moderate intensity exercise. Moderate intensity means that you are moving enough to start to sweat.";
"ARTICLE_DESCRIPTION" = "What you need to know about exercise during and after pregnancy.";
"SECTION5_HEADER" = "Exercise After Pregnancy";
"ARTICLE_TITLE" = "Exercise During and After Pregnancy";
"SECTION2_HEADER" = "Why is Exercise Important?";
"SECTION3_PARAGRAPH1" = "Overall, if you’re healthy and you aren’t experiencing any concerns with your pregnancy, it’s recommended to exercise regularly. The safest exercises are ones where you’re unlikely to fall, get hit in the abdomen, or overheat.";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH1" = "Exercise is a great way to support your overall health and it’s particularly important if you’re pregnant. That said, there are so many changes in your body, it can be hard to know how and when you should exercise.";
"SECTION5_PARAGRAPH1" = "Activity and exercise should begin as soon as you are cleared by your care team. Complications and the type of birth you have--vaginal or cesarean--can affect the amount of recovery time you need before you’re cleared. Exercise after pregnancy is important for several reasons, including prevention of depression or blood clots. Exercise can also help you get to the postpartum weight that is healthy for you. Adding abdominal exercises, or pelvic floor exercises—sometimes called Kegel exercises—can also help with recovery.";
"SECTION2_PARAGRAPH1" = "People who exercise regularly while they’re pregnant have a higher chance of vaginal birth. They also have a lower chance of several complications including gestational diabetes or hypertension, preterm birth, or low birth weight infants. There are also benefits to your mood and mental health.";
"SECTION4_HEADER" = "Exercise Intensity During Pregnancy";
"SECTION4_PARAGRAPH2" = "When you exercise while pregnant, it’s important to be aware of your intensity, and not over exert yourself. Because it’s normal for your heart rate to increase during pregnancy, heart rate is not the best indication of exercise intensity. Instead, you can use a ‘talk test’ as an easy way to make sure you are not over-exerting yourself. If you can talk or respond to questions comfortably, you are probably exercising at the right intensity. If you can’t, you may want to lower the intensity.";
"VIEW_TITLE" = "Cycle Tracking Article";
"SECTION3_PARAGRAPH2" = "Some examples of exercises that have been well studied and found to be safe include walking, indoor cycling, aerobic exercises, yoga, pilates, and dancing. Resistance exercises like weight lifting or stretching as well as water-based exercise like swimming and water aerobics are also considered safe.";
"SECTION3_PARAGRAPH3" = "Exercises that should be avoided include skiing, surfing, and gymnastics, because there is a high chance of falling or injury. You should also avoid contact sports, like basketball or soccer. Exercising outdoors when it is very hot, or doing yoga or pilates in a hot room can cause you to overheat.";
